      <div class="note n-blue">
        <div class="n-lbl">The golden rule</div>
        <div class="n-txt">Every execution is a brand-new, throwaway pod. When the job finishes, the pod disappears. No
          shared state. No leftover processes. This makes it safe, scalable, and reproducible.</div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- LAYERS -->
    <section class="section" id="layers">
      <div class="sec-lbl">Step 1 · Architecture</div>
      <h2 class="sec-h">Three layers. Three owners. Never mix them.</h2>
      <p class="sec-sub">Before writing a single line, understand what goes where. Each layer has one job and one team
        responsible for it. This separation is what makes the platform work.</p>
      <div class="persona-bar">
        <span class="persona persona-dev">⚙️ Platform</span>
        <span class="persona persona-ops">👩‍💻 Developer / Platform</span>
      </div>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div class="layers">
        <div class="layer ly1">
          <div class="l-badge">Platform team owns this · Never rebuild it yourself</div>
          <div class="l-title">🐳 The Hop Runtime Image (hop-sge)</div>
          <div class="l-sub">The engine. Contains Apache Hop, all enterprise plugins, and the Java runtime. Rarely
            changes. Your Dockerfile inherits FROM this image — you never modify it.</div>
          <div class="l-detail"><span>Apache Hop engine</span><span>All custom plugins pre-installed</span><span>Java
              runtime
              embedded</span><span>Published to Artifactory</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="layer ly2">
          <div class="l-badge">Jenkins builds this automatically on every merge</div>
          <div class="l-title">📦 Your Application Image</div>
          <div class="l-sub">Runtime Image + your code, baked together. This is the artifact that gets promoted through
            DEV → QA → UAT → PROD without ever being rebuilt. What you tested is what runs in production.</div>
          <div class="l-detail"><span>Inherits hop-sge</span><span>Your pipelines &amp; workflows</span><span>Your
              scripts</span><span>Base config (non-env-specific)</span><span>Tagged with semantic version</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="layer ly3">
          <div class="l-badge">OpenShift creates this per execution</div>
          <div class="l-title">☁️ The OpenShift Job (one run = one pod)</div>
          <div class="l-sub">A short-lived pod that pulls your Application Image, mounts EFS and secrets at runtime,
            then runs your workflow. When done, it disappears. No leftover state, no shared server.</div>
          <div class="l-detail"><span>Pulls your image from Artifactory</span><span>Mounts EFS for
              data</span><span>Injects ConfigMap + Secrets</span><span>Runs hop-run.sh</span><span>Terminates on
              completion</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- RUNTIME BUILDS -->
    <section class="section" id="runtime-builds">
      <div class="sec-lbl">Step 1b · Platform Builds</div>
      <h2 class="sec-h">How the Runtime Image (hop-sge) gets built</h2>
      <p class="sec-sub">The hop-sge image your Dockerfile inherits from isn't magic — it's the output of two Jenkins
        pipelines owned by the platform team. One fires when Apache Hop releases a new version. The other fires when you
        update your custom plugins or JDBC drivers. Both produce the same image name, just a new version tag.</p>
      <div class="persona-bar">
        <span class="persona persona-ops">⚙️ Platform — owns both pipelines</span>
        <span class="persona persona-dev">👩‍💻 Developer — triggers Plugin Build when JARs change</span>
      </div>
      <div class="divider"></div>

      <!-- Build flow -->
      <div class="flow-bar">
        <div class="fn">
          <div class="fi" style="background:#FFF3E0">
            <div class="fi-hop">Hop</div>
          </div>
          <div class="fl">New Hop version</div>
          <div class="fs">Apache release</div>
        </div>
        <div class="fa">→</div>
        <div class="fn">
          <div class="fi" style="background:#FEF3E2"><svg
