    <!-- DOCKERFILE -->
    <section class="section" id="dockerfile">
      <div class="sec-lbl">Step 2 · Build</div>
      <h2 class="sec-h">What goes in your Dockerfile</h2>
      <p class="sec-sub">Your Dockerfile is the recipe for your Application Image. It only contains things baked in at
        build time — code and structure, never config or secrets. Jenkins runs it automatically on every merge.</p>
      <h2 class="sec-h">Who will create this Dockerfile</h2>
      <p class="sec-sub">Jenkins CI/CD templated pipelines will create it by default. But developers can also create and
        modify it as needed to override the default CI/CD template.</p>

      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="fc">
          <div class="fc-hd">
            <div class="fc-icon" style="background:#EFF6FF"><svg
                style="width:19px;height:19px;filter:invert(29%) sepia(89%) saturate(1000%) hue-rotate(190deg)"
                viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <use href="#docker" />
              </svg></div>
            <div>
              <div class="fc-fn">Dockerfile</div>
              <div class="fc-tag">Build-time only. Lives in your Bitbucket repo root.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fc-bd">
            <div class="fc-what">Everything here is <strong>frozen at build time</strong>. Changing it means a new image
              version.</div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><strong>Include:</strong> your pipelines (.hwf/.hpl), workflows, scripts, shared lookup CSVs, base
                project config</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule no">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><strong>Never include:</strong> passwords, API keys, database hostnames, anything that changes
                between DEV and PROD</div>
            </div>
            <div class="note n-amber" style="margin-top:4px">
              <div class="n-lbl">Common mistake</div>
              <div class="n-txt">Do not hardcode database hosts or file paths inside your pipeline XML. If it changes
                between environments, it belongs in ConfigMap — not baked in.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="fc">
          <div class="fc-hd">
            <div class="fc-icon" style="background:#F0FDF4"><svg
                style="width:19px;height:19px;filter:invert(40%) sepia(70%) saturate(600%) hue-rotate(80deg)"
                viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <use href="#jfrog" />
              </svg></div>
            <div>
              <div class="fc-fn">Artifactory Registry</div>
              <div class="fc-tag">Where Jenkins pushes your image after building.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fc-bd">
            <div
              style="background:#F0FDF4;border:1px solid #BBF7D0;border-radius:var(--r);padding:14px;margin-bottom:12px">
              <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:8px;margin-bottom:10px;font-weight:700;color:#059669">
                <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 30 30">
                  <rect width="30" height="30" rx="5" fill="#10B981"></rect><text x="15" y="20" text-anchor="middle"
                    font-size="11" font-weight="900" fill="#fff">JF</text>
                </svg>
                Docker Repositories
              </div>
              <div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--slate2);line-height:1.5">
                <div style="margin-bottom:8px">
                  <div style="font-weight:600;color:#047857;margin-bottom:4px">Approved Runtime Images (Immutable)</div>
                  <div style="font-family:JetBrains Mono,monospace;font-size:10px;color:var(--muted)">
                    hop-runtime:2.15-v1, 2.15-v2, <strong>2.15-v3</strong> ✓</div>
                </div>
                <div style="text-align:center;color:var(--green);margin:6px 0">↓</div>
                <div>
                  <div style="font-weight:600;color:#047857;margin-bottom:4px">Application Images (Immutable)</div>
                  <div style="font-family:JetBrains Mono,monospace;font-size:10px;color:var(--muted)">
                    customer-load:1.2.7, 1.2.8, <strong>1.2.9 (Latest)</strong></div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="fc-what">Jenkins pushes the finished image tagged with a semantic version (e.g. <code
                style="font-family:JetBrains Mono,monospace;font-size:11px;background:#F1F5F9;padding:2px 5px;border-radius:3px">1.0.0</code>).
              OpenShift pulls from here — it never builds anything itself.</div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div>Same image SHA promoted through all environments — zero rebuilds</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule no">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div>Never use <code
                  style="font-family:JetBrains Mono,monospace;font-size:11px;background:#FEF2F2;padding:2px 5px;border-radius:3px">:latest</code>
                — always pin to a version tag</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="fc full">
          <details>
            <summary class="fc-hd">
              <div class="fc-icon" style="background:#EFF6FF"><svg
                  style="width:19px;height:19px;filter:invert(29%) sepia(89%) saturate(1000%) hue-rotate(190deg)"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                  <use href="#docker" />
                </svg></div>
              <div>
                <div class="fc-fn">Dockerfile — annotated example</div>
                <div class="fc-tag">Copy this, replace values, commit to your repo root</div>
              </div>
              <div class="view-code-btn">Toggle Code</div>
            </summary>
            <div class="cw" style="border:none;border-radius:0;border-top:1px solid var(--border)">
              <pre><span class="cmt"># Layer 1: inherit the central Hop runtime (never change this line yourself)</span>
<span class="cmd">FROM</span> <span class="str">artifactory.myorg.com/hop/hop-runtime:2.15-v3</span>

<span class="cmt"># Layer 2: bake in YOUR code ─────────────────────────────────────────────────</span>

<span class="cmt"># Hop pipelines and workflows</span>
<span class="cmd">COPY</span> <span class="arg">hop/pipelines/    /app/hop/pipelines/</span>
<span class="cmd">COPY</span> <span class="arg">hop/workflows/    /app/hop/workflows/</span>

<span class="cmt"># Helper scripts (startup wrapper, utilities)</span>
<span class="cmd">COPY</span> <span class="arg">scripts/          /app/scripts/</span>

<span class="cmt"># Base project config — things that NEVER change between environments</span>
<span class="cmt"># (pipeline metadata, project.json, shared lookup CSVs)</span>
<span class="cmd">COPY</span> <span class="arg">config/base/      /app/config/base/</span>

<span class="cmt"># Set permissions</span>
<span class="cmd">RUN</span> <span class="arg">chmod +x /app/scripts/*.sh</span>

<span class="cmt"># Entrypoint: reads ConfigMap + Secrets at runtime, merges into variables.json</span>
<span class="cmt"># then hands off to hop-run.sh</span>
<span class="cmd">ENTRYPOINT</span> <span class="val">["/app/scripts/entrypoint.sh"]</span></pre>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ENTRYPOINT -->
    <section class="section" id="entrypoint">
      <div class="sec-lbl">Step 2b · The glue script</div>
      <h2 class="sec-h">entrypoint.sh — how config reaches Hop</h2>
      <p class="sec-sub">This is the one script developers always wonder about. It runs first inside every pod, reads
        all injected env vars (from ConfigMap + Secret), writes them into Hop's <code
          style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:13px;background:#F1F5F9;padding:2px 6px;border-radius:4px">variables.json</code>,
        then hands off to <code
          style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:13px;background:#F1F5F9;padding:2px 6px;border-radius:4px">hop-run.sh</code>.
        Keep it in <code
          style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:13px;background:#F1F5F9;padding:2px 6px;border-radius:4px">scripts/entrypoint.sh</code>
        in your repo.</p>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="fc">
          <div class="fc-hd">
            <div class="fc-icon" style="background:#F0FDF4"><span style="font-size:17px">⚙️</span></div>
            <div>
              <div class="fc-fn">What entrypoint.sh does (in order)</div>
              <div class="fc-tag">Runs automatically at pod startup — you never call it directly.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fc-bd">
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><strong>1.</strong> Checks that <code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;background:#F1F5F9;padding:1px 4px;border-radius:3px">/etc/hop-secrets/hop-properties.json</code>
                is mounted</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><strong>2.</strong> Copies it directly to <code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;background:#F1F5F9;padding:1px 4px;border-radius:3px">/app/config/variables.json</code>
                — no parsing, no iteration</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><strong>3.</strong> Overlays the 7 ConfigMap env vars so DevOps can override behaviour at runtime
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><strong>4.</strong> Execs <code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;background:#F1F5F9;padding:1px 4px;border-radius:3px">hop-run.sh</code>
                as PID 1 so signals reach it correctly</div>
            </div>
            <div class="note n-amber" style="margin-top:8px">
              <div class="n-lbl">Why simpler than the env-var approach</div>
              <div class="n-txt">The old pattern iterated all OS env vars and wrote them to JSON — fragile, noisy, and
                exposed every system env var to Hop. Now it's one <code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">cp</code> plus a 7-key overlay. If the
                file isn't there, it fails fast with a clear error before Hop even starts.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="fc">
          <div class="fc-hd">
            <div class="fc-icon" style="background:#F0FDF4"><span style="font-size:17px">📋</span></div>
            <div>
              <div class="fc-fn">variables.json — what Hop actually reads</div>
              <div class="fc-tag">Generated fresh on every pod start. Never committed to Git.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fc-bd">
            <div class="cw">
              <pre><span class="cmt"># /app/config/variables.json — generated at runtime, never committed to Git</span>
<span class="cmt"># = hop-properties.json (from Secret) + 7 ConfigMap overlays</span>
<span class="punct">{</span>
  <span class="cmt">// From Secret JSON (hop-properties.json) ──────────────</span>
  <span class="str">"DB_HOST"</span><span class="punct">:</span>        <span class="val">"prod-oracle.myorg.internal"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
  <span class="str">"DB_PORT"</span><span class="punct">:</span>        <span class="val">"1521"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
  <span class="str">"DB_SCHEMA"</span><span class="punct">:</span>      <span class="val">"FINANCE_PROD"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
  <span class="str">"DB_PASSWORD"</span><span class="punct">:</span>    <span class="val">"superSecret1"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
  <span class="str">"INPUT_FOLDER"</span><span class="punct">:</span>   <span class="val">"/efs/finance/prod/input"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
  <span class="str">"SSH_KEY_PATH"</span><span class="punct">:</span>   <span class="val">"/etc/hop-secrets/id_rsa"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
  <span class="str">"PGP_KEY_PATH"</span><span class="punct">:</span>   <span class="val">"/etc/hop-secrets/pgp-private.key"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
  <span class="cmt">// From ConfigMap (overlaid by entrypoint.sh) ──────────</span>
  <span class="str">"HOP_ENVIRONMENT"</span><span class="punct">:</span><span class="val">"prod"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
  <span class="str">"LOG_LEVEL"</span><span class="punct">:</span>      <span class="val">"INFO"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
  <span class="str">"BATCH_SIZE"</span><span class="punct">:</span>     <span class="val">"5000"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
  <span class="str">"WORKFLOW_NAME"</span><span class="punct">:</span>  <span class="val">"workflows/customer-load.hwf"</span>
<span class="punct">}</span></pre>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="fc full">
          <details>
            <summary class="fc-hd">
              <div class="fc-icon" style="background:#F0FDF4"><span style="font-size:17px">⚙️</span></div>
              <div>
                <div class="fc-fn">entrypoint.sh — full annotated script</div>
                <div class="fc-tag">Copy this into scripts/entrypoint.sh in your repo</div>
              </div>
              <div class="view-code-btn">Toggle Code</div>
            </summary>
            <div class="cw" style="border:none;border-radius:0;border-top:1px solid var(--border)">
              <pre><span class="kw">#!/bin/bash</span>
<span class="cmd">set</span> <span class="kw">-euo pipefail</span>
<span class="cmd">exec</span> <span class="arg">/opt/hop/hop-run.sh \
  --environment</span> <span class="str">"${HOP_ENVIRONMENT}"</span> <span class="punct">\</span>
  <span class="arg">--variables-file /etc/hop-secrets/hop-properties.json \
  --parameters</span> <span class="str">LOG_LEVEL="${LOG_LEVEL}",BATCH_SIZE="${BATCH_SIZE}",THREAD_COUNT="${THREAD_COUNT}"</span> <span class="punct">\</span>
  <span class="arg">-j</span> <span class="str">"${WORKFLOW_NAME}"</span> <span class="punct">\</span>
  <span class="arg">-r</span> <span class="str">"${HOP_RUNNER}"</span></pre>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- CONFIGMAP -->
    <section class="section" id="configmap">
      <div class="sec-lbl">Step 3 · Configuration</div>
      <h2 class="sec-h">ConfigMap — runtime behaviour switches only</h2>
      <p class="sec-sub">ConfigMap holds <strong>operational knobs</strong> — values a DevOps engineer or DBA might
        legitimately need to read or change in an incident without touching code or secrets. It is intentionally thin.
        Everything that describes where your data lives or how your infrastructure is shaped belongs in the Secret JSON
        file, not here.</p>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="fc">
          <div class="fc-hd">
            <div class="fc-icon" style="background:#FFF3E0"><svg style="width:19px;height:19px" viewBox="0 -1 34 34">
                <use href="#os" />
              </svg></div>
            <div>
              <div class="fc-fn">What goes in ConfigMap — 7 keys, intentionally</div>
              <div class="fc-tag">The test: would DevOps or DBA need to change this in an incident without touching
                secrets?</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fc-bd">
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;background:#F1F5F9;padding:1px 4px;border-radius:3px">HOP_ENVIRONMENT</code>
                — <code style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">dev</code> / <code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">qa</code> / <code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">prod</code></div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;background:#F1F5F9;padding:1px 4px;border-radius:3px">LOG_LEVEL</code>
                — <code style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">INFO</code> / <code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">DEBUG</code> / <code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">ERROR</code> — flip without touching
                secrets</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;background:#F1F5F9;padding:1px 4px;border-radius:3px">BATCH_SIZE</code>
                — tune throughput in prod without a redeployment</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;background:#F1F5F9;padding:1px 4px;border-radius:3px">THREAD_COUNT</code>
                — parallelism knob, adjusted by DevOps under load</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;background:#F1F5F9;padding:1px 4px;border-radius:3px">WORKFLOW_NAME</code>
                — lets DevOps redirect to a different workflow in an incident</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;background:#F1F5F9;padding:1px 4px;border-radius:3px">HOP_RUNNER</code>
                — <code style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">local</code> / <code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">remote</code> — lets DevOps switch
                runner without touching secrets</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;background:#F1F5F9;padding:1px 4px;border-radius:3px">JAVA_OPTS</code>
                — heap tuning, e.g. <code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">-Xms512m -Xmx1024m</code></div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule no">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><strong>Not here:</strong> DB hostnames, ports, schema names, EFS paths, SFTP hosts — those reveal
                infrastructure topology → Secret JSON</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule no">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><strong>Not here:</strong> any password, key, token, or passphrase → Secret JSON</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="fc">
          <div class="fc-hd">
            <div class="fc-icon" style="background:#FEF3C7"><span style="font-size:17px">💡</span></div>
            <div>
              <div class="fc-fn">Why DB_HOST belongs in the Secret JSON, not here</div>
              <div class="fc-tag">A common mistake from Pentaho teams.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fc-bd">
            <div class="fc-what">Hostnames and ports look harmless but they're <strong>reconnaissance material</strong>
              — they describe your internal network topology. Anyone with OpenShift console read access can see
              ConfigMaps. Keeping <code style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">DB_HOST</code>,
              <code style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">DB_SCHEMA</code>, EFS paths, SFTP
              hosts, and Kafka brokers in the Secret JSON means your infrastructure shape is visible only to those with
              Secret access — which is a much tighter RBAC boundary.
            </div>
            <div class="note n-amber" style="margin-top:8px">
              <div class="n-lbl">The split in one sentence</div>
              <div class="n-txt">ConfigMap = <em>how Hop behaves</em>. Secret JSON = <em>where Hop connects and what
                  credentials it uses</em>. If you're not sure, ask: "does this reveal infrastructure?" If yes → Secret
                JSON.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="fc full">
          <details>
            <summary class="fc-hd">
              <div class="fc-icon" style="background:#FFF3E0"><svg style="width:19px;height:19px" viewBox="0 -1 34 34">
                  <use href="#os" />
                </svg></div>
              <div>
                <div class="fc-fn">configmap-prod.yaml — annotated example</div>
                <div class="fc-tag">7 keys only. One per environment. Applied by Jenkins during deployment.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="view-code-btn">Toggle Code</div>
            </summary>
            <div class="cw" style="border:none;border-radius:0;border-top:1px solid var(--border)">
              <pre><span class="kw">apiVersion</span><span class="punct">:</span> v1
<span class="kw">kind</span><span class="punct">:</span> ConfigMap
<span class="kw">metadata</span><span class="punct">:</span>
  <span class="kw">name</span><span class="punct">:</span> hop-config
  <span class="kw">namespace</span><span class="punct">:</span> hop-prod
<span class="kw">data</span><span class="punct">:</span>
  <span class="cmt"># Runtime behaviour — operational knobs only ─────────────────────────────────</span>
  <span class="cmt"># Everything else (hostnames, paths, credentials) is in the Secret JSON file.</span>

  <span class="key">HOP_ENVIRONMENT</span><span class="punct">:</span>  <span class="str">"prod"</span>
  <span class="key">LOG_LEVEL</span><span class="punct">:</span>        <span class="str">"INFO"</span>             <span class="cmt"># flip to DEBUG for prod investigation</span>
  <span class="key">BATCH_SIZE</span><span class="punct">:</span>       <span class="str">"5000"</span>
  <span class="key">THREAD_COUNT</span><span class="punct">:</span>     <span class="str">"4"</span>
  <span class="key">WORKFLOW_NAME</span><span class="punct">:</span>    <span class="str">"workflows/customer-load.hwf"</span>   <span class="cmt"># redirect here in an incident</span>
  <span class="key">HOP_RUNNER</span><span class="punct">:</span>       <span class="str">"local"</span>
  <span class="key">JAVA_OPTS</span><span class="punct">:</span>        <span class="str">"-Xms512m -Xmx1024m"</span>

<span class="cmt"># ── What is NOT here (and why) ────────────────────────────────────────────────</span>
<span class="cmt"># DB_HOST, DB_PORT, DB_SCHEMA    → infrastructure topology → Secret JSON</span>
<span class="cmt"># INPUT_FOLDER, OUTPUT_FOLDER    → reveals EFS layout     → Secret JSON</span>
<span class="cmt"># SFTP_HOST, KAFKA_BROKERS       → reveals network shape   → Secret JSON</span>
<span class="cmt"># DB_PASSWORD, API_TOKEN         → credentials             → Secret JSON</span></pre>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SECRETS -->
    <section class="section" id="secrets">
      <div class="sec-lbl">Step 4 · Secrets</div>
      <h2 class="sec-h">Secrets — two files, two purposes</h2>
      <p class="sec-sub">Everything that was in Pentaho's <code
          style="font-family:JetBrains Mono,monospace;font-size:13px;background:#F1F5F9;padding:2px 6px;border-radius:4px">kettle.properties</code>
        — connection strings, hostnames, paths, credentials — lives in one Secret as a mounted JSON file. SSH keys, PGP
        keys, and keystores live in the same Secret as separate mounted files. No individual env var keys scattered
        across YAML. One Secret, two file types, clean boundary.</p>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div class="grid">

        <div class="fc">
          <div class="fc-hd">
            <div class="fc-icon" style="background:#FEF2F2"><span style="font-size:17px">📄</span></div>
            <div>
              <div class="fc-fn">File Type 1 — hop-properties.json</div>
              <div class="fc-tag">The kettle.properties equivalent. Everything Hop reads as ${VARIABLE}.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fc-bd">
            <div class="fc-what" style="margin-bottom:10px">One JSON blob containing all connection details, paths, and
              credentials. Stored as a single Secret entry, mounted as a file. <code
                style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">entrypoint.sh</code> copies it directly to
              <code style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">variables.json</code> — no parsing, no
              iteration.
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div>DB host, port, schema, service name</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div>DB username and password</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div>EFS paths: input, output, archive, error folders</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div>SFTP host, port, username, password</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div>API tokens, OAuth secrets</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div>Kafka bootstrap servers, S3 bucket names</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div>AES key, AES IV, keystore/truststore passphrases</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div>PGP key file path references (the paths, not the keys themselves)</div>
            </div>
            <div class="note n-green" style="margin-top:8px">
              <div class="n-lbl">Why this mirrors kettle.properties exactly</div>
              <div class="n-txt">In Pentaho it was one flat file. Here it's one flat JSON file. Same mental model, same
                atomicity — either the whole config is present or it isn't. No risk of a key being missing from one
                environment because someone forgot to add it to a YAML list.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="fc">
          <div class="fc-hd">
            <div class="fc-icon" style="background:#FEF2F2"><span style="font-size:17px">🔑</span></div>
            <div>
              <div class="fc-fn">File Type 2 — key files (SSH, PGP, JKS)</div>
              <div class="fc-tag">Binary or multi-line files. Mounted alongside the JSON, same Secret.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fc-bd">
            <div class="fc-what" style="margin-bottom:10px">SSH private keys, PGP private and public keys, Java
              keystores (<code style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">.jks</code>), and TLS
              certificates. Each stored as a separate entry in the same Secret, mounted at a known path. The path is
              referenced in <code
                style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">hop-properties.json</code> so your
              pipeline knows where to find them.</div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><code style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">pgp-private.key</code> → mounted
                at <code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">/etc/hop-secrets/pgp-private.key</code>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><code style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">pgp-public.key</code> → mounted
                at <code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">/etc/hop-secrets/pgp-public.key</code>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><code style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">id_rsa</code> → mounted at <code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">/etc/hop-secrets/id_rsa</code> (chmod
                400)</div>
            </div>
            <div class="rule yes">
              <div class="rd"></div>
              <div><code style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">keystore.jks</code> → mounted at
                <code style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">/etc/hop-secrets/keystore.jks</code>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="note n-blue" style="margin-top:8px">
              <div class="n-lbl">How your pipeline references a key</div>
              <div class="n-txt">Set <code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">"PGP_KEY_PATH": "/etc/hop-secrets/pgp-private.key"</code>
                in <code style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">hop-properties.json</code>. Your
                Hop transform reads <code
                  style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">${PGP_KEY_PATH}</code>. The path and the
                key file are both secret, both in the same mount. Clean.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="fc full">
          <details>
            <summary class="fc-hd">
              <div class="fc-icon" style="background:#FEF2F2"><span style="font-size:15px">🔐</span></div>
              <div>
                <div class="fc-fn">hop-secrets.yaml — full annotated example (both file types)</div>
                <div class="fc-tag">One Secret, all secret material. Applied per environment by Jenkins.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="view-code-btn">Toggle Code</div>
            </summary>
            <div class="cw" style="border:none;border-radius:0;border-top:1px solid var(--border)">
              <pre><span class="kw">apiVersion</span><span class="punct">:</span> v1
<span class="kw">kind</span><span class="punct">:</span> Secret
<span class="kw">type</span><span class="punct">:</span> Opaque
<span class="kw">metadata</span><span class="punct">:</span>
  <span class="kw">name</span><span class="punct">:</span> hop-secrets
  <span class="kw">namespace</span><span class="punct">:</span> hop-prod
<span class="kw">stringData</span><span class="punct">:</span>

  <span class="cmt"># ── FILE TYPE 1: hop-properties.json ─────────────────────────────────────────</span>
  <span class="cmt"># The kettle.properties equivalent. entrypoint.sh copies this to variables.json</span>
  <span class="cmt"># Everything Hop reads as ${VARIABLE} lives here.</span>
  <span class="key">hop-properties.json</span><span class="punct">: |</span>
    <span class="punct">{</span>
      <span class="cmt">// Database ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────</span>
      <span class="str">"DB_HOST"</span><span class="punct">:</span>          <span class="val">"prod-oracle.myorg.internal"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
      <span class="str">"DB_PORT"</span><span class="punct">:</span>          <span class="val">"1521"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
      <span class="str">"DB_SCHEMA"</span><span class="punct">:</span>        <span class="val">"FINANCE_PROD"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
      <span class="str">"DB_SERVICE"</span><span class="punct">:</span>       <span class="val">"ORCLPRD"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
      <span class="str">"DB_USERNAME"</span><span class="punct">:</span>      <span class="val">"hop_user"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
      <span class="str">"DB_PASSWORD"</span><span class="punct">:</span>      <span class="val">"superSecret1"</span><span class="punct">,</span>

      <span class="cmt">// EFS paths ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────</span>
      <span class="str">"INPUT_FOLDER"</span><span class="punct">:</span>     <span class="val">"/efs/finance/prod/input"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
      <span class="str">"OUTPUT_FOLDER"</span><span class="punct">:</span>    <span class="val">"/efs/finance/prod/output"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
      <span class="str">"ARCHIVE_FOLDER"</span><span class="punct">:</span>   <span class="val">"/efs/finance/prod/archive"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
      <span class="str">"ERROR_FOLDER"</span><span class="punct">:</span>     <span class="val">"/efs/finance/prod/errors"</span><span class="punct">,</span>

      <span class="cmt">// SFTP ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────</span>
      <span class="str">"SFTP_HOST"</span><span class="punct">:</span>        <span class="val">"sftp.myorg.internal"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
      <span class="str">"SFTP_PORT"</span><span class="punct">:</span>        <span class="val">"22"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
      <span class="str">"SFTP_USERNAME"</span><span class="punct">:</span>    <span class="val">"hop_sftp"</span><span class="punct">,</span>

      <span class="cmt">// Key file paths — the files themselves are mounted separately ─────────</span>
      <span class="str">"SSH_KEY_PATH"</span><span class="punct">:</span>     <span class="val">"/etc/hop-secrets/id_rsa"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
      <span class="str">"PGP_KEY_PATH"</span><span class="punct">:</span>     <span class="val">"/etc/hop-secrets/pgp-private.key"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
      <span class="str">"PGP_PUBKEY_PATH"</span><span class="punct">:</span>  <span class="val">"/etc/hop-secrets/pgp-public.key"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
      <span class="str">"KEYSTORE_PATH"</span><span class="punct">:</span>    <span class="val">"/etc/hop-secrets/keystore.jks"</span><span class="punct">,</span>

      <span class="cmt">// Encryption / signing ─────────────────────────────────────────────────</span>
      <span class="str">"AES_KEY"</span><span class="punct">:</span>          <span class="val">"base64encodedAESkey=="</span><span class="punct">,</span>
      <span class="str">"AES_IV"</span><span class="punct">:</span>           <span class="val">"base64encodedAESiv==="</span><span class="punct">,</span>
      <span class="str">"KEYSTORE_PASS"</span><span class="punct">:</span>    <span class="val">"myKeystorePass"</span><span class="punct">,</span>
      <span class="str">"PGP_PASSPHRASE"</span><span class="punct">:</span>   <span class="val">"myPgpPassphrase"</span><span class="punct">,</span>

      <span class="cmt">// API ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────</span>
      <span class="str">"API_TOKEN"</span><span class="punct">:</span>        <span class="val">"abc123xyz"</span>
    <span class="punct">}</span>

  <span class="cmt"># ── FILE TYPE 2: key files ────────────────────────────────────────────────────</span>
  <span class="cmt"># Binary / multi-line files. Mounted at /etc/hop-secrets/ inside the pod.</span>
  <span class="cmt"># Paths are referenced in hop-properties.json above — pipeline uses ${SSH_KEY_PATH}.</span>
  <span class="key">id_rsa</span><span class="punct">: |</span>
    <span class="val">-----BEGIN OPENSSH PRIVATE KEY-----</span>
    <span class="val">b3BlbnNzaC1rZXktdjEAAAAA...</span>
    <span class="val">-----END OPENSSH PRIVATE KEY-----</span>

  <span class="key">pgp-private.key</span><span class="punct">: |</span>
    <span class="val">-----BEGIN PGP PRIVATE KEY BLOCK-----</span>
    <span class="val">lQdGBGV...</span>
    <span class="val">-----END PGP PRIVATE KEY BLOCK-----</span>

  <span class="key">pgp-public.key</span><span class="punct">: |</span>
    <span class="val">-----BEGIN PGP PUBLIC KEY BLOCK-----</span>
    <span class="val">mQINBGV...</span>
    <span class="val">-----END PGP PUBLIC KEY BLOCK-----</span>

  <span class="cmt"># keystore.jks is binary — store base64-encoded in data: not stringData:</span>
  <span class="cmt"># data:</span>
  <span class="cmt">#   keystore.jks: /u3+7QAAAAIAAAABAAA... (base64 of .jks file)</span></pre>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>

        <div class="fc full">
          <details>
            <summary class="fc-hd">
              <div class="fc-icon" style="background:#FEF2F2"><span style="font-size:17px">⚠️</span></div>
              <div>
                <div class="fc-fn">deployment.yaml — how the Secret is mounted</div>
                <div class="fc-tag">One volume mount gives the pod access to all files in the Secret.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="view-code-btn">Toggle Code</div>
            </summary>
            <div class="cw" style="border:none;border-radius:0;border-top:1px solid var(--border)">
              <pre><span class="cmt"># In your Job spec — one volume for all secret files</span>
<span class="key">volumes</span><span class="punct">:</span>
  <span class="punct">-</span> <span class="kw">name</span><span class="punct">:</span> hop-secrets
    <span class="key">secret</span><span class="punct">:</span>
      <span class="kw">secretName</span><span class="punct">:</span> hop-secrets
      <span class="key">defaultMode</span><span class="punct">:</span> <span class="val">0400</span>        <span class="cmt"># read-only, owner only — required for SSH keys</span>

<span class="key">volumeMounts</span><span class="punct">:</span>
  <span class="punct">-</span> <span class="kw">name</span><span class="punct">:</span> hop-secrets
    <span class="key">mountPath</span><span class="punct">:</span> <span class="str">"/etc/hop-secrets"</span>
    <span class="key">readOnly</span><span class="punct">:</span> true
<span class="cmt"># Result inside pod:</span>
<span class="cmt">#   /etc/hop-secrets/hop-properties.json   ← entrypoint.sh reads this</span>
<span class="cmt">#   /etc/hop-secrets/id_rsa                ← SSH client reads this</span>
<span class="cmt">#   /etc/hop-secrets/pgp-private.key       ← GnuPG reads this</span>
<span class="cmt">#   /etc/hop-secrets/pgp-public.key</span>
<span class="cmt">#   /etc/hop-secrets/keystore.jks</span></pre>
              <div class="note n-red" style="margin-top:8px">
                <div class="n-lbl">Security rule</div>
                <div class="n-txt">Never log the contents of <code
                    style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">hop-properties.json</code> or any key
                  file. Never print <code
                    style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">${DB_PASSWORD}</code> or <code
                    style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">${AES_KEY}</code> to stdout. Dynatrace
                  captures stdout — treat it as a public audit trail.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- DEPLOYMENT.YAML -->
    <section class="section" id="deployment">
      <div class="sec-lbl">Step 5 · Deployment</div>
      <h2 class="sec-h">deployment.yaml — the plug board</h2>
      <p class="sec-sub">The deployment file tells OpenShift exactly what to run, how much resource to give it, which
        ConfigMap and Secret to inject, where to mount EFS, and what command to execute. It contains no code, no
        passwords, and no logic — only references.</p>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div class="note n-blue" style="margin-bottom:var(--gap)">
        <div class="n-lbl">What deployment.yaml does NOT contain</div>
        <div class="n-txt">No code. No passwords. No file paths. No business logic. It references other things by name —
          the image tag, the ConfigMap name, the Secret name, the PVC name. Think of it as a wiring panel that connects
          all the other files together at runtime.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="fc full">
          <details>
            <summary class="fc-hd">
