      </div>
      <div style="font-size:14px;font-weight:700;color:var(--slate);margin-bottom:14px">Promotion gates — same image,
        zero rebuilds</div>
      <div class="gates">
        <div class="gate">
          <div class="gc" style="background:#3B82F6">D</div>
          <div class="gn">DEV</div>
          <div class="gt">Auto on merge</div>
        </div>
        <div class="garr">→</div>
        <div class="gate">
          <div class="gc" style="background:#8B5CF6">Q</div>
          <div class="gn">QA</div>
          <div class="gt">QA lead approves</div>
        </div>
        <div class="garr">→</div>
        <div class="gate">
          <div class="gc" style="background:#F59E0B">U</div>
          <div class="gn">UAT</div>
          <div class="gt">UAT sign-off</div>
        </div>
        <div class="garr">→</div>
        <div class="gate">
          <div class="gc" style="background:#EF4444">P</div>
          <div class="gn">PROD</div>
          <div class="gt">Change manager</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="note n-green">
        <div class="n-lbl">The zero-rebuild guarantee</div>
        <div class="n-txt">The Docker image SHA that passed QA testing is the exact same image that runs in PROD.
          Jenkins tags it once and promotes it unchanged. What you tested is what runs in production — no surprises from
          environment-specific builds.</div>
      </div>
      <div
        style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fit,minmax(280px,1fr));gap:var(--gap);margin-top:var(--gap)">
        <div class="note n-blue">
          <div class="n-lbl">Image tagging — why git SHA not BUILD_ID</div>
          <div class="n-txt">Jenkins <code style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">BUILD_ID</code>
            is a sequential number that resets if Jenkins is reinstalled and means nothing in Artifactory. Use <code
              style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">version-gitSHA</code> (e.g. <code
              style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">1.0.0-abc1234</code>) — you can trace any
            running pod back to the exact commit in Bitbucket.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="note n-amber">
          <div class="n-lbl">Job failure &amp; retry — set backoffLimit</div>
          <div class="n-txt">Add <code
              style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px">spec.backoffLimit: 1</code> to your
            OpenShift Job YAML. Without it, a failing pod retries 6 times by default — running your pipeline 6× and
            leaving 6× the partial output on EFS. For most ETL jobs, 1 retry is enough; set 0 if your pipeline is not
            idempotent.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- DYNATRACE -->
    <section class="section" id="observability">
      <div class="sec-lbl">Step 7 · Observability</div>
      <h2 class="sec-h">Dynatrace — your eyes on every run</h2>
      <p class="sec-sub">Every pod writes to stdout. OpenShift collects it. Dynatrace ingests, correlates, and surfaces
        problems before you know something went wrong — no configuration inside your pipeline required.</p>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div class="dyna-card">
        <div class="dyna-hd">
          <div class="dyna-ic"><svg
              style="width:20px;height:20px;filter:invert(55%) sepia(80%) saturate(500%) hue-rotate(190deg)"
              viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <use href="#dynatrace" />
            </svg></div>
          <div>
            <div class="dyna-hs">Metrics · Distributed Traces · Logs · Anomaly Detection — all correlated automatically
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="dyna-grid">
          <div class="dyna-chip">
            <div class="dc-lbl">Metrics</div>
            <div class="dc-t">Pod &amp; infrastructure metrics</div>
            <div class="dc-s">CPU, memory, pod restarts, job duration, EFS I/O — from OpenShift nodes via OneAgent. Set
              SLOs directly in Dynatrace.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="dyna-chip">
            <div class="dc-lbl">Distributed tracing</div>
            <div class="dc-t">Trace every pipeline run</div>
            <div class="dc-s">Each Hop job appears as a trace. Drill into slow transforms, compare run times, spot
              regressions — no code changes needed.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="dyna-chip">
            <div class="dc-lbl">Log management</div>
            <div class="dc-t">Unified log search</div>
            <div class="dc-s">Pipeline logs to stdout → OpenShift captures → Dynatrace ingests. Search across all runs,
              filter by job name or env, alert on error patterns.</div>
          </div>

        </div>
        <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fit,minmax(280px,1fr));gap:var(--gap)">
          <div class="note n-navy">
            <div class="n-lbl">Developer logging tip</div>
            <div class="n-txt">Always log to stdout — never to a file inside the container (it disappears when the pod
              exits). Structure your lines with a consistent prefix like <code
                style="font-family:JetBrains Mono,monospace;font-size:11px">[LOAD][2024-03-15][customer-load]</code> so
              Dynatrace queries are fast.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="note n-blue">
            <div class="n-lbl">Debug checklist</div>
            <div class="n-txt">1. Spin up a debug pod using <strong>your app image</strong> (not hop-sge — it won't have
              your pipelines): <code
                style="font-family:JetBrains Mono,monospace;font-size:11px">oc run hop-debug --image=artifactory.myorg.com/hop/your-app:1.0.0-abc1234 -- sleep 3600</code><br>2.
              Shell in: <code style="font-family:JetBrains Mono,monospace;font-size:11px">oc rsh hop-debug</code><br>3.
              Check paths: <code
                style="font-family:JetBrains Mono,monospace;font-size:11px">/opt/hop /app/hop /efs /etc/secrets</code><br>4.
              Run: <code
                style="font-family:JetBrains Mono,monospace;font-size:11px">hop-run.sh -j workflows/test.hwf -e dev</code><br>5.
              Check logs in Dynatrace.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
    </section>

